		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Dominionism</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">This article is about the political-religious concept.  For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Dominion_(disambiguation)" title="Dominion (disambiguation)">Dominion (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<p><b>Dominionism</b> describes, in several distinct ways, a tendency among some <a href="/wiki/Conservative_Christianity" title="Conservative Christianity">conservative</a> <a href="/wiki/Politics" title="Politics">politically-active</a> <a href="/wiki/Christianity" title="Christianity">Christians</a>, especially in the <a href="/wiki/United_States_of_America" title="United States of America" class="mw-redirect">United States of America</a>, to seek influence or control over secular civil government through political action—aiming either at a nation governed by Christians, or a nation governed by a conservative <a href="/wiki/Law_in_Christianity" title="Law in Christianity" class="mw-redirect">Christian understanding of biblical law</a>. The use and application of this terminology is a matter of controversy.</p>
